# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1997-nba-finals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The **1947 BAA Finals** was the championship round of playoffs following the inaugural Basketball Association of America (BAA)'s 1946–47 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Philadelphia Warriors of the Eastern Division faced the Chicago Stags of the Western Division for the inaugural championship, with Philadelphia having home court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Hall of Fame inductee Joe Fulks played for the Warriors in the series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Philadelphia was not the Eastern Division champion but advanced to the championship round by winning a four-team playoff among the Eastern and Western Division runners-up.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Meanwhile, the Eastern and Western Division champions, Washington Capitols and Chicago Stags, played one long series to determine the other finalist, a best-of-seven series that Chicago won 4–2.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] In the runners-up bracket, Philadelphia and New York from the East had first eliminated St.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Louis and Cleveland from the West, then faced each other, all in best-of-three series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The format was repeated in 1948, and generated another champion from the runners-up bracket.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The five games of the final series were played in seven days, with no days off between consecutive games in the same city (twice).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Division champions Washington and Chicago had played the six games of their semifinal series from April 2 to 13, although they too took no days off between consecutive games in the same city (twice).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] In total, the entire playoff tournament lasted a total of 20 days.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] This would be the Stags only appearance in the Finals; the franchise would fold three years later.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] It would be another 44 years before a Chicago club played for a pro basketball championship, when the Chicago Bulls won the 1991 NBA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Joe Fulks then scored 29 points in the second half, including 21 in the fourth quarter.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Angelo Musi, a guard out of Temple University, scored 19 points himself for Philadelphia as well.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Stags took an astounding 129 shots, but only knocked down 26 of them, a 20.2 shooting percentage which made it easy for the Warriors to win, 84–71.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Fulks was not the scorer he was in Game 1, but he did not have to be, because five other Warrior players scored in double figures, including 18 points from forward Howie Dallmar and 16 from guard Jerry Fleishman.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Chicago did take a brief 69–68 lead until Philadelphia center Art Hillhouse came alive in the fourth quarter.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] He scored 7 out of the last 10 points for the Warriors, in route to a second Philadelphia win, 85–74.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Stags staved off elimination and avoided a sweep with a one-point victory.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] With less than a minute remaining, Howie Dallmar snapped an 80–80 tie by nailing a jump shot to seal the very first championship for the Warriors.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The **1948 BAA Finals** was the championship round of the Basketball Association of America's 1947–48 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The defending 1947 BAA champions Philadelphia Warriors of the Eastern Division faced the Baltimore Bullets of the Western Division, with Philadelphia having home court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a Baltimore-based team.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Baltimore was not the Western Division champion but advanced to the championship round by winning a four-team playoff among the Eastern and Western Division runners-up.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Meanwhile, the Eastern and Western Division champions, Philadelphia Warriors and St.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Louis Bombers, played one long series to determine the other finalist, a best-of-seven series that Philadelphia won 4–3.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] In the runners-up bracket, Baltimore and Chicago from the West had first eliminated New York and Boston from the East, then faced each other in a best-of-three series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The format was used only twice, in 1947 and 1948, and generated two champions from the runners-up bracket.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The six games of the final series were played in *twelve* days, with at least one day off except prior to the decisive game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Louis had played the seven games of their semifinal series in *fifteen* days, March 23 to April 6, with at least one day off before every game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The entire playoff tournament extended 30 days.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] As of 2023, this is the only BAA/NBA Finals which a now-defunct team won (as opposed to teams that changed names and/or moved to other cities in later years).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The **1949 BAA Finals** was the championship round following the Basketball Association of America (BAA)'s 1948–49 season, its third and last.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] Later that year, the BAA and National Basketball League merged to create the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] 6'10" George Mikan and the Minneapolis Lakers proved dominant.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] They routed the Washington Capitols in six games.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] This was the first of several successive NBA titles for the Lakers.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] It was the beginning of the George Mikan and the Lakers Dynasty.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a Minneapolis-St.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The six games of the final series were played in ten days – Monday, April 4, to Wednesday, April 13 – with one day off except after game three, the first of three played in Washington (Minneapolis led 3–0).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] Prior to its start, however, Minneapolis had been idle for five days, having qualified on the preceding Tuesday; Washington idle for only one day, having qualified on Saturday.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The entire playoff tournament extended 23 days.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The **1950 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s inaugural 1949–50 season following the merger of the National Basketball League (NBL) and the Basketball Association of America (BAA).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The defending 1949 BAA champions and Central Division champions Minneapolis Lakers faced the Eastern Division champion Syracuse Nationals in a best-of-seven series with Syracuse having home-court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] In the event, six games were played in 16 days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 8 and 9, in Syracuse and incorporating two subsequent Sunday games in Minneapolis.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Counting a Central Division tiebreaker played on Monday, March 20, the entire postseason tournament spanned five full weeks to Sunday, April 23.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The NBA was arranged in three divisions (for its first season only) and the first two rounds of the 1950 NBA playoffs generated three Division champions.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] With the league's best regular season record, Syracuse had earned a place in the Finals by winning the Eastern Division title on the preceding Sunday, and had been five days idle while the Central and Western champions had played a best-of-three series mid-week.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] In Game 1, the Lakers won on a buzzer beating shot by sub Bob "Tiger" Harrison, the first known case of a buzzer beater in the Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Six-foot-eight-inch (2.03 m) Dolph Schayes of Syracuse led his team out to the finals after a 16.8 ppg average during the regular season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] George Mikan, however, averaged 27.4 ppg and led the league.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Mikan would lead the Lakers past Syracuse in six games.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The championship was the Lakers third professional championship in a row after winning the NBL championship in 1948 and the BAA championship in 1949.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] While the NBA was considered a new league at the time, it later retconned the three preceding BAA seasons as part of its own history, and thus presents the 1950 Finals as its fourth championship series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The **1951 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the 1951 NBA playoffs, which concluded the National Basketball Association 1950–51 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] It featured an all-New York matchup Western Division champion Rochester Royals faced the Eastern Division champion New York Knickerbockers in a best-of-seven series with Rochester having home-court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the only time the NBA Finals ever featured two teams from the same state.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Rochester won the first three games, two at home, but New York won the next three, two at home.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] It was the first BAA or NBA Finals (spanning 1947 to 1951) that extended to a seventh-game conclusion, a 4-point win by Rochester at home on Saturday, April 21.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The seven games were played in fifteen days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 7 and 8, in Rochester and incorporating one game in Rochester on each following weekend.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Three Wednesday or Friday games were played in New York City.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The entire postseason tournament spanned 33 days in which both Rochester and New York played 14 games.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals appeared in their first NBA finals by defeating the Fort Wayne Pistons in the semifinals and the two-time defending champion Minneapolis Lakers in the division finals while the Knickerbockers defeated the Boston Celtics in the semifinals and the Syracuse Nationals in the division finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the first finals appearance for both teams, and the first Finals with two teams that had not made a finals appearance since the 1947 BAA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Rochester / Cincinnati Royals / Kansas City / Sacramento Kings won their first ever NBA Championship.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Knickerbockers led 74–72 with under three minutes later but Arnie Risen and Bob Davies (who combined for 44 points scored in the game) managed to draw quick shots and free throws in the final minutes to give the Royals a 79–75 victory.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Contrary to today's practices, there was no trophy presentation or a parade.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the first and to date last title for the Rochester Royals, who would move to Cincinnati, Ohio for the 1958 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals would spend 15 years mired in mediocrity before moving to Kansas City, Missouri in 1972, changing their name in the process to the Kings.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] One notable highlight was their appearance in the 1981 NBA playoffs, in which their 40–42 team reached the Western Conference finals before losing to the Houston Rockets, who also had a 40–42 record.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Kings moved to Sacramento, California in 1985, where they have remained to this day.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The team reached the Western Conference finals in 2002, where they lost in seven games to the Los Angeles Lakers in a highly controversial series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Kings’ 2002 Western Conference final run was the closest the team got to reaching the NBA Finals in the modern era.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals/Kings have the longest NBA title drought, the longest NBA Finals appearance drought, the longest active championship round appearance drought in all four of the American major pro sports leagues, and the third longest championship drought in North American sports.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This would be the Knickerbockers' first of three consecutive appearances in the Finals, but they would lose all three times.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] They would not return to the Finals until 1970, which they won.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The **1952 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the 1952 NBA playoffs, which concluded the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s 1951–52 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The Western Division champion Minneapolis Lakers faced the Eastern Division champion New York Knickerbockers in a best-of-seven series with Minneapolis having home-court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Minneapolis won game one and the teams thereafter alternated victories, Minneapolis winning the decisive game by a 17-point margin at home on Friday, April 25.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] All but Game 7 were played in the teams' secondary arenas: the Lakers played at the Saint Paul Auditorium, while the Barnum circus bumped the Knickerbockers from Madison Square Garden to the 69th Regiment Armory.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The seven games were played in fourteen days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 12 and 13, in Minneapolis/St.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Paul for games five and seven on the following Saturday and Friday.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Meanwhile, three Wednesday or Friday games were played in New York City.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The entire postseason tournament spanned 39 days in which Minneapolis played 13 games and New York 14.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] This was the first playoff meeting between these two teams.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1953-nba-finals] The **1953 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the 1953 NBA playoffs, which concluded the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s 1952–53 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1953-nba-finals] By winning four games to one, the Lakers won their fifth title in six years dating from 1948, the club's final season in the National Basketball League.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1953-nba-finals] The five games were played in seven days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 4 and 5, in Minneapolis and concluding there on the following Friday.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1953-nba-finals] Meanwhile, two mid-week games were played in New York City.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1953-nba-finals] The entire postseason tournament spanned 25 days in which Minneapolis played 12 games, New York 11.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The **1997 NBA Finals** was the championship series of the National Basketball Association's (NBA) 1996–97 season and conclusion of the season's playoffs.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Western Conference champion Utah Jazz took on the defending NBA champion and Eastern Conference champion Chicago Bulls for the title, with the Bulls holding home court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The series were played under a best-of-seven format, with the first 2 games in Chicago, the next 3 games in Salt Lake City, and the last 2 games in Chicago.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] For the fifth time in as many Finals appearances, Michael Jordan was named NBA Finals MVP.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls and Jazz won a combined 133 regular season games, the second most in Finals history behind the previous year's 136.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Until 2016, the 1997 NBA Finals was the last to feature teams that won a total of at least 130 regular season games.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] For the Chicago Bulls, the campaign was almost identical to their record-breaking 1995–96 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] They began the season 12–0, and by the All-Star break, were 42–6, putting them on pace to win 70 games for a second year in a row.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] But some late-season injuries and poor play, including Scottie Pippen's failed attempt at a game-winning three-pointer in the Bulls' final regular season game against the New York Knicks, and the Bulls settled for a league-best 69–13 record.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] This tied the 1971–72 Los Angeles Lakers for the second-best regular season, only behind the 1995–96 Bulls (72–10) at the time.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] 19 years later, the 2015–16 Golden State Warriors (73–9) would break the wins record.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In the playoffs, the Bulls swept the Washington Bullets in the first round, dispatched the Atlanta Hawks in five games in the second round, then defeated the Miami Heat in five games in the Eastern Conference finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz emerged as a force in the Western Conference as far back as the mid-1980s, powered by its All-Star duo of point guard John Stockton and power forward Karl Malone.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] They advanced to the Western Conference finals three times between 1992 and 1996 (1992, 1994 and 1996), but lost on each occasion.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] However, a different story was written for the 1996–97 season.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Powered by league MVP Karl Malone, along with the talented John Stockton, the Jazz finally asserted themselves atop the Western Conference, finishing with a franchise-record 64 wins.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Also notable on the season was Utah's complete rebrand, as they replaced their classic "J-Note" logo and Mardi Gras colors with a bold, gradient "Purple Mountain" motif.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In the playoffs, Utah swept the Los Angeles Clippers in the opening round and eliminated the Los Angeles Lakers in five games in the second round.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Utah then eliminated the Houston Rockets to advance to their first NBA Finals in franchise history, thanks to John Stockton's buzzer-beating, three-point shot in Game 6 of the Western Conference finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Another storyline heading into the Finals was Jazz head coach Jerry Sloan coaching against his former team as a player.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Sloan made the All-Star game twice with the Bulls and was a key player on Dick Motta’s defensive-minded teams throughout the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Despite Michael Jordan scoring a game-high 44 points, the Jazz rallied with strong performances from Karl Malone (36 points, 15 rebounds) and John Stockton (12 points, 13 assists) and gave the Bulls' their first loss of the season on November 23 at the Delta Center.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Finals were played using a 2–3–2 site format, where the first two and last two games are held at the team with home court advantage's (Chicago's) home court (United Center).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Had the Western Conference finals between the Jazz and the Houston Rockets reached a game 7, the Finals would have started on Wednesday, June 4 and followed the similar Wednesday-Friday-Sunday rotation.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Despite injuring his foot in the Eastern Conference finals against Miami, Scottie Pippen helped the Bulls to an 84–82 victory over Utah on Sunday.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He scored 27 points while Jordan scored 31.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls trailed by one in the 4th, yet were able to grab an 81–79 lead after Pippen blocked Antoine Carr, then made his third 3-pointer with 1:11 remaining.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] However, John Stockton answered with a 3 of his own with 51.7 seconds left to give Utah an 82–81 lead.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Michael Jordan made 1 of 2 free throws with 35.8 seconds left to tie it at 82.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Then, Karl Malone was fouled by Rodman with 9.2 seconds left and had a chance to give Utah the lead.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Scottie famously psyched him out, saying, "Just remember, the mailman doesn't deliver on Sundays, Karl", before he stepped up to the line.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan got the rebound and quickly called a time-out with 7.5 seconds left.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] With the game on the line, the Bulls put the ball in Jordan's hands.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He dribbled out most of the waning seconds, then launched a 20-footer (game-winning shot) that went in at the buzzer to give Chicago a 1–0 series lead, after which he pumped his fist in triumph.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The fist-pumping often draws comparisons to another famous Jordan reaction to a buzzer-beater, when he leaped into the air after hitting The Shot that eliminated the Cleveland Cavaliers in Game 5 of the 1989 Eastern Conference quarterfinals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan joined Cliff Hagan in Game 6 in 1957, Jerry West in Game 3 in 1962, Larry Wright in Game 1 in 1979, and Dennis Johnson in Game 4 in 1985 as the only NBA Finals buzzer-beaters.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] To date, there has not been another buzzer-beating shot to win a Finals game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] After a hard-fought first quarter, the Bulls took control of the game with a 12–0 second-quarter run.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Utah's 31 points in the first half was only one point above an NBA low.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Karl Malone, who missed those two key free throws in Game 1, had another bad night, making only 6 of 20 field goals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Dennis Rodman nailed a late 3-pointer to put the Bulls up 97–85.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Utah's fans welcomed their proud Western Conference champs with force.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] During the introductions of the Jazz's starting lineups, the Bulls players plugged their ears, due to the loud cheers and fireworks within the Delta Center.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Chicago Bulls started off the first three quarters with mediocre play, despite Scottie Pippen tying a then-Finals record with seven 3-pointers.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Utah was led by Karl Malone, who scored 37 points and had 10 rebounds.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Chicago attempted a 4th-quarter comeback, cutting a 24-point deficit down to 7, but Utah ultimately won its first game of the series.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] With the Bulls trailing by 18 points in the second quarter, Michael Jordan threw down an alley-oop slam which drew loud boos from the crowd.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Dennis Rodman defended his poor performance in Game 3 with a vulgar remark denigrating Mormons and was fined a then record $50,000 for this remark and CKE Restaurants dropped his television commercials permanently.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He apologized, claiming he was not aware that Mormon referred to a religion and intended his remark at obnoxious Jazz fans.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Due to the extremely loud Jazz fans in Game 3, Bulls coach Phil Jackson wore a pair of ear plugs.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] A tight game with many lead changes throughout, the Jazz led by five after the first quarter, but trailed by five at halftime.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The score was tied going into the fourth quarter.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Late in the game, Michael Jordan made a fast break dunk to give the Bulls a 71–66 lead, but John Stockton buried a momentum-shifting three-pointer at the top of the key to cut the deficit to 71–69.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan made a jumper to give the Bulls a 73–69 lead with 2:01 remaining, but the Bulls would not score again.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz pulled to within one when Stockton stole the ball from Jordan and made two free throws at the other end.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] On the next possession, Stockton grabbed a rebound from a Jordan miss and threw a full-court pass to Karl Malone for a layup with 44.5 seconds left that put Utah in front for good, 74–73.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] After Stockton made the assist, he jumped up into the air several times pumping his fist.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] After some Bulls misses, Karl Malone made two free throws with 17 seconds left to put the Jazz up by three.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz's 12–2 run tied the series at two games apiece.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Delta Center grew so loud that during the final moments of the game when Bryon Russell made the dunk that iced the game, Marv Albert was unable to be clearly heard.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The 78–73 score was one of the lowest scores in NBA Finals history.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jackson later wrote that the team's equipment manager "had mistakenly served our players Gaterlode, a high-carbohydrate drink, instead of Gatorade," making the team "sluggish...
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Game 5, known as "**The Flu Game**", was one of Michael Jordan's most memorable games.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] At 2:30 a.m. on Tuesday morning, Jordan woke up and began to experience vomiting and diarrhea, and called his personal trainer to his hotel room, where he was found lying curled up in the fetal position, shaking, and sweating profusely.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He hardly had the strength to sit up in bed and requested a doctor.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He was diagnosed with a stomach virus or food poisoning, likely caused by a pizza ordered the night before.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan eventually claimed it was food poisoning in the 2020 docuseries *The Last Dance*.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls' athletic trainers told Jordan that there was no way he could play the next day, but Jordan insisted that he play.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz were a perfect 10–0 at home in the postseason up until that point, and a third consecutive win would give them the series lead.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls needed Jordan to assist them, as it was a critical game, and despite his sickness, Jordan got out of bed at 5:50 p.m. on Wednesday, just in time for the 7 o'clock tip-off at the Delta Center.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan was weak as he stepped on the court for Game 5, and missed team warmups.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] At first, he displayed little energy, and John Stockton, along with reigning MVP Karl Malone, led the Jazz to a 16-point lead (36–20) in the second quarter.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] But Jordan slowly began to make shots despite lacking his usual speed.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He scored 17 points in the quarter as the Bulls ended the half with a large run cutting the Jazz lead to four (53–49).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] While Jordan was fatigued in the third and sitting on the bench, Utah was able to reclaim the lead and stretched it to 8 points (77–69).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan shot well again in the fourth quarter, scoring 15 points.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] With 46.4 seconds left and Chicago down 85–84, he was fouled and went to the free throw line.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He made the first to tie the game, but missed the second.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Toni Kukoč got the offensive rebound to Jordan, who dribbled back to allow the offense to set up.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He passed the ball to Pippen, who was quickly double-teamed.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Pippen then passed the ball back to a now-unguarded Jordan, who made a 3-point shot to give the Bulls an 88–85 lead with 25 seconds remaining in the game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] A Greg Ostertag dunk brought the Jazz back within one point, but Luc Longley answered with a dunk of his own, and Chicago held on for a victory when John Stockton missed the first of two free throws in front of the stunned crowd.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] With only a few seconds remaining and the game's result safely in Chicago's favor, Jordan collapsed into Scottie Pippen's arms, creating an iconic image that has come to symbolize The Flu Game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Malone was the high-scorer for the Jazz with 19 points but shot poorly during the game, air-balling an off-balance shot on the possession prior to Jordan's 3-pointer.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Malone finished the second half 1-for-6 from the field.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan played 44 minutes, finishing the game with 38 points, 7 rebounds, 5 assists, 3 steals and 1 block.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Michael Jordan hadn't fully recovered from his illness, but he was feeling much better and led the Bulls with 39 points.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Chicago struggled in the first half, scoring just 37 points and making only 9 of 27 field goals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] With the Bulls struggling in the third quarter, Jordan dunked after a steal, bringing the crowd to its feet and Jud Buechler buried a 3 to help give the Bulls the momentum.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls trailed by 9 early in the fourth quarter, but went on a 10–0 run to take their first lead since the opening minutes when Steve Kerr hit a 3-pointer, but the Jazz regained the lead and the game remained one possession until the final score.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In the final minutes, Jordan's fadeaway jumper extended the Bulls lead to 3, before Bryon Russell hit a 3-pointer with 1:44 left to tie the game at 86.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The two teams failed to score on their next possessions.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Shandon Anderson then missed a reverse layup.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz argued that this was due to Pippen grabbing the rim before the shot, causing the basketball standard to shake.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] However, the officials ruled that the ball had no chance of going in.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Dennis Rodman grabbed the rebound and called time-out with 28 seconds left in a tie game.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Jazz expected Jordan to take the final shot.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Instead, Jordan drew a double-team, then passed to a wide-open Steve Kerr, who hit a 17-footer with 5 seconds left to send the United Center into a frenzy.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Jordan finished with 39 points to go along with 11 rebounds and four assists, and he was named Finals MVP for the 5th time.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] This would also be the last United Center championship celebration until eighteen years later when the NHL's Chicago Blackhawks beat the Tampa Bay Lightning to win the 2015 Stanley Cup.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Marv Albert was the play-by-play announcer for his seventh straight NBA Finals for the *NBA on NBC*.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] It was his third straight NBA Finals working with color analysts Matt Guokas and Bill Walton.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] This would be the last NBA Finals that Albert would announce in the 1990s because of a sex scandal that would force NBC Sports to fire him later in 1997.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] During these NBA Finals, NBC Sports' Hannah Storm became the first woman to serve as pre-game host of an NBA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] She would continue in this role for the next three NBA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] NBC Sports also used Ahmad Rashad (Bulls sideline) and Jim Gray (Jazz sideline) as the sideline reporters.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] This would be the only NBA Finals on NBC during the 1990s that would not include Bob Costas in any capacity.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] He had served as the pre-game host from 1991 to 1996.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The next year, during the 1998 NBA Finals, Costas served as the play-by-play announcer, a role in which he would continue until after the 2000 NBA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The local NBC affiliates of the participating teams included WMAQ-TV (Chicago) and KSL-TV (Salt Lake City).
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Both teams met again in the Finals in 1998, the first time the same two teams met in the NBA Finals since 1989, when the Lakers and Pistons went up against each other.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Only this time, the Jazz had home-court advantage.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] The Bulls won that series in 6 games, highlighted by Michael Jordan's last shot as a Bull in Game 6.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] (nicknamed the Mailman) before crucial free throws in Game 1.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Nationally, Karl Malone, the MVP of the league in the regular season, was criticized heavily for a subpar NBA Finals.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] Dennis Rodman and Brian Williams forced Malone into taking more jump shots than he had in any playoff series in his career to that point.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In the 1997 Finals, Malone shot 44% compared to 53% in the regular season and 60% at the free throw line compared to 78%.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In Game 1, Malone missed 2 free throws with 9 seconds left, which left Michael Jordan to hit the game winner.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In Game 5, he went 7-for-17 from the floor and 5-for-9 at the free throw line for 19 points in a Jazz two point loss.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In Game 6, he went 7-for-15 from both the field and free throw line in what turned out to be a close four point loss.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] This was the only Bulls' championship Brian Williams was a part of.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In 1998, Williams changed his name to Bison Dele to honor his Native American (Cherokee) and African ancestry.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] At the age of 30, he retired after the 1998–99 season, walking away from the remaining five years and US$36.45 million on his contract with the Detroit Pistons rather than be traded.
[src:1997-nba-finals/1997-nba-finals] In 2002, Dele, his girlfriend Serena Karlan, and boat captain Bertrand Saldo were killed by his Dele's brother, Miles Dabord, after the two got into an argument aboard Dele's boat near Tahiti across the Pacific Ocean.
